<HEADLINE>
Criteria for posting an RFD
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> Steve Bonine &lt;s...@pobox.com&gt; </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-10-14T09:52:00 </POSTDATE>
There has been discussion recently concerning the policy for posting
RFDs.  I would like to float an idea for formalizing a policy related to
this issue.  If there's sufficient support, I'll write it up and submit
it as an RFD.  As a side effect, it might demonstrate whether it's
possible to conduct a coherent discussion in news.groups.

For purposes of this discussion, let's divide submitted RFDs into two
categories -- the ones that might pass eventually, and the ones that
don't have any chance of passing a Board vote.  It's obviously
impossible to determine in advance which RFDs will pass and which won't,
but I do believe that it's possible to deduce in some cases that a
particular RFD cannot garner sufficient support to obtain a majority of
YES votes when the Board votes.  In these cases it's a waste of time to
go through the formal process of posting the RFD, debating it, voting,
and announcing a result.

The goal is to establish a threshold that a submitted RFD must meet to
continue the process.  This threshold should be low, but consistent.  I
suggest a procedure analogous to the motion/second procedure used in
traditional in-person meetings.

In a traditional formal meeting, one person *makes a motion* and someone
else *seconds the motion*.  Normally the second is a routine matter that
takes only (no pun intended) seconds.  On rare occasions, a motion dies
for want of a second.  In this case, it's obvious that the motion would
not have passed and the meeting attendees save the time to debate it.

Extending this to the electronic meeting that the Board conducts, I
suggest that each RFD be required to receive an affirmative &quot;second&quot;
from two Board members before moving forward.  If there aren't two Board
members who think that the proposal has sufficient merit to even be
published, it's obvious that the proposal will not pass a Board vote.
Just as in the traditional parliamentary world, a &quot;second&quot; does not
imply that the person seconding is going to vote for the proposal later;
it simply states that they feel that it has sufficient merit to be
discussed further.

The problem that I see with this idea is the height of the bar that it
puts in place.  Maybe it's too high, and useful RFDs will be screened
out.  Maybe it's too low, and it won't screen out anything.  Maybe it's
actually not a change in procedure at all and this is effectively what's
already happening.  It's just an idea, and I'm curious what comments it
will elicit.
</POST>
