Here is an outline of how I see the process:

1. An RFD is posted to n.a.n.

2. The RFD is relayed to the board.

3. The board decides whether to publish the RFD in n.a.n.

3.1 If the RFD is rejected, a rejection notice is
sent to the proponent.

3.2 If the RFD is published, the steps for participating
in the discussion are outlined in the RFD itself.

3.2.1 Discussion ensues.

3.2.2 Discussion is brought to an end.  Either the
proponent withdraws the RFD or the board makes a
formal decision on it.

Your questions deal with step 3.  Under the rules of consensus,
the board lets the chair seek agreement informally.  Two cases
are possible:

&quot;If I hear no objections in [some time specified], I will publish
the RFD in n.a.n.&quot;

&quot;If I hear no objections in [some time specified], I will NOT publish
the RFD in n.a.n.&quot;

If there is an objection in either case, more formal procedures
should kick in.  I don't see any reason why the board can't take
a formal vote on the question of whether a particular RFD should
be published--except that it takes about a week or so to go through
the formal vote.  But that is the only reliable method to determine
what the board as a whole wants to do with the RFD.

The board can create subcommittees and assign votetakers to run
particular votes, so IF formal procedures are needed, they wouldn't
become too burdensome for any one member.

There is an alternate model of what happens in step 3.  Some people
(understandably) use the norms for moderated groups as a guide
to thinking about how the decision is made.  In this model, a
moderation policy is set for n.a.n, just like any other newsgroup.
All posts that arguably meet the formal standards of the moderation
policy have to be published regardless of what the board thinks of
them.

I am opposed to using that model in step 3.  It sets too low a
bar for publication and would not keep n.a.n from coming under
flood attacks.

We have recently rewritten and expanded the policy on the kinds of
proposals that are discouraged:

http://www.big-8.org/dokuwiki/doku.php?id=policies:discouraged

This list gives some idea of the standards that are applied in
sifting out RFDs.  I don't think we can give a clear and
distinct definition of what are nonsense proposals, trolls,
flames, or other kinds of snowballs.  There is no way that I
can see to formalize the procedure further than giving these
general guidelines.  There are exceptions to every rule,
except the rule that there are exceptions to every rule;
humans are the final exception handlers in any system like
this.

